explanation:
UT_GetStubEntry - Need the prototype/definition to confirm whether it is a simple accessor or contains for-loops or persistent side-effects. If it contains a for loop or has side-effects, that could affect MISRA analysis even though it is called outside a for-statement in this function.

UT_SetHandlerFunction - Required to inspect its implementation for any for-loops or modifications of objects that could be used as loop counters/flags elsewhere. Also to see whether it expands to macros or inlined code containing loops.

UT_DoSetHookFunction - UT_SetHandlerFunction calls this; include its definition because loops or side-effects inside this callee could be relevant to overall behavior and to determine whether any loop-related objects are modified.

UT_DefaultStubImpl - This function is called unconditionally at the end of UT_ExecuteBasicHandler. Its body must be inspected for any for-loops (or macros expanding to for-loops) that would be part of the observable behavior triggered by UT_ExecuteBasicHandler.

UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs - UT_DefaultStubImpl calls this; include it to fully cover nested callees that could contain for-loops or modify objects that might be loop counters/flags.

UT_EntryKey_t - The type of the FuncKey parameter may be a typedef or struct that, if used by callees, could be read/modified in loops; the type definition is needed to understand what objects might be used as loop counters or flags.

UT_HandlerFunc_t - The type of DefaultHandler is needed to determine whether passing it (or setting it) could expand into code with loops or modify loop-related objects (e.g., if it is a macro or inline function type).

UT_StubEntry (return type of UT_GetStubEntry) - Knowledge of the structure/type returned by UT_GetStubEntry is required to see whether comparisons to NULL or subsequent use could relate to loop counters/flags or whether the function actually returns an object with side-effects.

UT_ENTRYTYPE_FINAL_HANDLER - The constant used as an argument to UT_GetStubEntry could be a macro with side-effects or expansion; include its definition to ensure it does not expand into loop constructs or modify objects relevant to loop well-formedness.
